<h1> Food </h1>
<p>Food was not of the highest quality at Manzanar. The Japanese are accustomed to their specific cuisine and style of eating. However, Manzanar food was based on military requirements and usually consisted of rice and vegetables as meat was rationed. </p>
<p>Food was served in mess halls where internees waited in long lines. A typical meal was syrupy fruit over rice with vegetables to the side. The camp usually added meat supplements to this. </p>
<p>Internees at Manzanar began cultivating livestock including chickens and hogs. They also began growing vegetables and fruit for consumption. Soy sauce and tofu were also made on premise. With these sources helping them reach back towards their origin, some new foods – more indicative of traditional cuisine – were invented and popularized.</p>
